### Footnotes

<span id="fn_164"></span>[82:1](sbe20024.htm#fr_169.md) It is clear from
verses 192-196 of the 13th chapter of the Râ*g*a-nigha*nt*u, written by
Narahari of Kashmîr in the thirteenth century A. D., that at that time
Vai*d*ûrya meant 'cat's-eye: But it is uncertain whether that was the
only meaning of the word ve*l*uriya at the time when this passage was
composed. (See especially V. 124, p. 25, of Dr. Richard Garbe's edition
in his work, 'Die Indischen Mineralien,' Leipzig, 1882.) See also
Professor Max Müller's interesting note at p. 266 of his 'What can India
teach us?'

<span id="fn_165"></span>[82:2](sbe20024.htm#fr_170.md) Kâ*k*amayo. There
was probably no glass in our modern sense of the word when the
*K*ullavagga was written. But kâ*k*a is a silicious earth, and some sort
of glass-like earthenware may very well have been in use. The phrase has
already occurred, together with all the others in this passage, at
Mahâvagga V, 8, 3, of foot-coverings, but is omitted in the list at
Khudda Sikkhâ V. 10.

<span id="fn_166"></span>[82:3](sbe20024.htm#fr_171.md) Gha*m*sîyati.
Literally, 'were rubbed.' See below, § 3, and our note below on V, 9, 2,
4.

<span id="fn_167"></span>[83:1](sbe20024.htm#fr_172.md) A*kkh*ûpiyanti. On
the use of this word, compare Mahâvagga VIII, 14, 1, where it is used of
inserting a slip of cloth in a torn garment.

<span id="fn_168"></span>[83:2](sbe20024.htm#fr_173.md) See our note above
on V, 8, I. Buddhaghosa says here likhitun ti tanu-kara*n*-atthây’
eta*m* vutta*m*. The 'shaping' may be by carving, adzing, or planing.

<span id="fn_169"></span>[83:3](sbe20024.htm#fr_174.md) Compare above, V,
8, 1, and see Buddhaghosa's note at p. 316 of the edition of the text.

<span id="fn_170"></span>[83:4](sbe20024.htm#fr_175.md) The reading is
corrupt; and therefore this rendering is merely conjectural. See H.O.'s
note at p. 316 of his edition of the text.

<span id="fn_171"></span>[83:5](sbe20024.htm#fr_176.md) On these split
crocodiles' teeth, see our note above on V, 1, 4.

<span id="fn_172"></span>[83:6](sbe20024.htm#fr_177.md) Rûpakoki*nn*âni
bhati-kamma-katâni. Buddhaghosa has nothing on these words. On the
second, see below, VI, 2, 7, and H.O.'s note on that passage at p. 321
of the edition of the text. It is most probable that the reading in both
passages should be bhatti-kamma, 'patchwork,' as further explained in
our note below on VI, 2, 7; and we have translated accordingly.

<span id="fn_173"></span>[84:1](sbe20024.htm#fr_178.md) Otâpetvâ. The word
has already occurred in Mahâvagga I, 25, 16. Compare Khudda Sikkhâ V. 6.

<span id="fn_174"></span>[84:2](sbe20024.htm#fr_179.md) Vodaka*m* katvâ.
Vodaka*m* bears, of course, the same relation to sa-udaka*m*, used just
before, as vagga does to samagga. The expression has occurred already at
Mahâvagga I, 25, 13.

<span id="fn_175"></span>[85:1](sbe20024.htm#fr_180.md) Vâta-ma*nd*alikâya.
So also in the next section and in the Bhikkhunî-vibhaṅga, Pâ*k*ittiya
96. The reading at *G*âtaka I, 72 is vâta-ma*nd*ala*m*.

<span id="fn_176"></span>[85:2](sbe20024.htm#fr_181.md) Mi*dh*ante. This
